Another solution would be to have a function creating a list of tasks. Example:
```
def deposit_tasks_facotry(deposit_class):
  @shared_task
  def index_deposit(deposit_uuid):
    deposit = deposit_class.get_record(deposit_uuid)
    deposit.indexer.index(deposit.fetch_published()[1])
  return [index_deposit]
```

Please move these 2 classes right after LibvirtComputeResource in opposite order to achieve alphabetical order like
```
class DockerComputeResource(AbstractComputeResource):
class LibvirtComputeResource(AbstractComputeResource):
class OVirtComputeResource(AbstractComputeResource):
class VMWareComputeResource(AbstractComputeResource):
```

Three remarks (before @ocefpaf will pep8 this) :smile: 

- the ( ) are redundant around the lambda function, they should go away;
- besides the fact this line is well over 80 lines it's anyways better to make it explicit:
```Python
if not style_function:
    style_function = lambda x: {}
self.style_funciton = style_function
```
- Finally, why did you not use a default a lambda function in the method signature? Is there some Python gotcha I'm not aware of, such as the default [] / {}? Unless there is, it's the cleanest way to do this.
